Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to the preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought about a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current large coalition, as well as a well-known strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly large losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphal return to the political scene at national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 per cent of the vote, the country's first political force, however, compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 per cent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent loses nearly nine percent of the vote, has ended even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties, particularly for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Again in early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
Voters visibly chastise them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations were made about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen on Monday at the extraordinary party leadership council.
Such an evolution would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election, which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the large SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
Nevertheless, in view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the free parties (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 per cent and BZÖ 11 per cent of the votes - the socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the popular party agreed with the populists (at the time the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ split) on a common government, which even raised sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he is planning to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently relies on this development.
The last party to have access to the parliament being the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell back, among the Austrian political parties, from the third to the fifth position.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four per cent limit and did not enter parliament.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India may cool down
If the problem of the Czech researchers accused in India of illegally collecting cockroaches could not be resolved, Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg said there would be a certain cooling down of Czech-Indian relations.
The minister said this today in New York, after meeting with his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not solved, then yes, some cooling would occur," he observed after the meeting, carried out following a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, on leaving the talks, that the executive could hardly intervene in judicial cases.
He mentioned, however, that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was relieved of the charge and fined, the central government could negotiate with the local government, that of Darjeling, the case being placed under its jurisdiction.
"His problem could be solved," said the minister.
According to Mukherjee, the best solution for Emil Kučera, who was sentenced to three years in prison, would be to appeal to a higher court.
Therefore, he could apply for bail and wait for the trial to be released, he explained.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner expressed himself in the same direction also during the talks.
"He advises to appeal to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned," said the head of Czech diplomacy.
The only way in which the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide convicts with "competent legal support", said the Indian Minister.
He also said that such assistance was already being provided by India.
"We want above all to keep with India the best relations, which have a tradition that continues over many years.
