"I've already received quite a lot of promises," he said only.
A Czech Arbitrator Fighting for the Seabed
It is approaching a mural electronic map, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are represented.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as well as the adjacent seafloor.
This area is as large as the continent itself," said the Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the thirty-member team of the United Nations Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, the Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
Ardour at work and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a world not so far known, rich in natural resources.
Oil, minerals and other mineral resources can be found there, but also living organisms for the time being unknown, which may contain the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A larger bottom than the land
The littoral states have now begun to vehemently aspire to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are indeed using their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of what is known as the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometres from the coast of the given country.
According to the Convention, the latter may claim exclusively all the resources of the continental Shelf.
"To simplify, the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea, is considered to be continental Shelf.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the 200 nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone," says Mikulka.
The request made by the country in question to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on numerous prospecting and costly metricities.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the Committee with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, namely those from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
For the time being, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," says Mikulka.
Australia's success, which was the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently experienced a worldwide resounding.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the depth of the seabed, which was allocated to it by the Commission last week, is 1.6 million square kilometres, representing the country's sixfold increase.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefit they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they plan, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention".
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no State enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, let us not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," said Director Mikulka, exaggerating that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed is now also owned by the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states in the former Eastern bloc within the framework of the "Interoceanmetal" joint organisation.
In 1991, the Commission obtained the status of the so-called "first-time investor" under the Convention, as well as investors from a few other states.
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, between Mexico, Hawaii and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is enlivened, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract over an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometres.
The area represents a polymetallic concretion-rich deposit containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," said Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, brings an example of such a concretion.
It recalls a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
