The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has, this time, been inspired by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating bee theft, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Centre have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan security shield.
This robot will allow brand vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan security shield.
But the most important thing is the eyes composed of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles that are located over a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"As it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
If so, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, " explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Moving Laboratory and principal engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down, nor diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotational function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
" Each second this device must only process information and act on it.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logics of prior maneuvers, that's why it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This represents the first car to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into standard cars in ten years after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
