Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, it was the third that put a draft new Constitution to the vote.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half the vote plus one.
On Sunday, two polls on the way out of the polling stations and a count from a non-governmental organization had announced a large victory for the "yes", setting it at between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday until Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly", he had assured, congratulating the Equatorians at the siege of Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales as well as his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place in a calm manner according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was about a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country essentially living from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
The project, which was carried out by Correa, elected in 2006, also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will be able to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and run for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services which the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando attacked the abductors of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back this Monday afternoon safe and sound in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at about 3.30 p.m. on a special plane at the military base at al-Maza, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to Maadi Hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," said Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, at the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been slammed from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It consists of 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official reported that 30 members of the special forces, carried on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunshots took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled," said the official, who demanded anonymity.
He reported that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle during a patrol with the kidnappers, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and stopping two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement had immediately denied.
