Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states help the Belgian-Holland bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. The three countries support, to the tune of EUR 11.2 billion, this financial and insurance institution also with interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also involving the European Central Bank and the European Commission's Competition Officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been growing for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions to be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy up almost half (49%) of the bank's capital in each country.
The bank will, without doubt, sell part of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the activities, essentially insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch organisation ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares started a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to be allowed to go into bankruptcy.
On Friday alone, the company's shares fell by 12 percent, reaching its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, shares have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's management, is not realistic.
The company's management is accused of the uncertainty of the overseas Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the $700 billion bailout plan, to be at the root of the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already received a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new Managing Director.
The financial agency was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received any substantive proposals.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was assaulted.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also purchased leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, health and life insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate based on information about his or her drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of information on the prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it amounts to entrusting its henhouse to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage, on the state of health of the client who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates to a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after they had read the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies the data concerning the purchase of the person's medicines within the last eighteen months. From this, the program determines himself, what disease the person suffers and what his state of health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducing, this refers to extremely high levels of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk factor, so there is no longer much to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still arise.
Among the disadvantages of this program are the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in research and analysis of data, and they must ask the patient for authorisation before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their shortcomings in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug use. In this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and the control of use is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the extension of the control circle of the authorities concerning enterprises specialized in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard admits that this is not enough and that is why he developed his program even further, which would make data transmission conditional upon the data subject's exclusive agreement.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus and ultimately, hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
Marseille's global menu
The European Union and India double their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be discussed.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power that should be given a wider right to speak in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit in Marseilles.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double the trade, which means an increase of about 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be too ambitious a target.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, and in this way air trade will also be able to flourish in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's largest trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation had been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on that subject had been mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade round has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its toxic releases by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as on the need for a global market at next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now visiting the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to news agency information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
