Found Steve Fossett's plane, the missing billionaire a year ago.
The wreck of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying on the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at 3000 metres above sea level in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
The Madera County sheriff, John Anderson, removed the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one on which Steve Fosset was travelling the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore stated that no human remains were found on or around the aircraft.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreck was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene, identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
In the sixth attempt, in 2002, he became the first man to complete the round the world on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and without stop.
Among all these records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
